{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473878"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11559"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.1,0.03,0.63,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4188"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4188"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33920"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1514"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40356"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-month-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever, poor feeding, lethargy and irritability. She has a history of multiple urinary tract infections, with the most recent one four months ago. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 146/min, blood pressure 82/45 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. The physical examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine dipstick shows leukocyte esterase and nitrites. Urinalysis reveals white blood cells. Urine culture results are pending. An ultrasound examination four months ago was unremarkable. A recent DMSA scan showed scarring at the upper pole of the right kidney. She is suspected to have vesicoureteric reflux and is scheduled for cystoscopy in three weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advice to use cranberry juice to reduce the recurrence of urinary tract infections","Urgent surgical correction of vesicoureteric reflux","Watchful waiting","Empirical intravenous antibiotics","Start daily antibiotic prophylaxis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the most appropriate next step in management is to administer \u003Cstrong\u003Eempirical intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E. The child presents with systemic symptoms (fever, lethargy, irritability) and signs of a urinary tract infection (UTI) on dipstick and urinalysis. Given her history of recurrent UTIs and evidence of renal scarring on DMSA scan, prompt treatment with intravenous antibiotics is crucial to prevent further renal damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranberry juice\u003C/strong\u003E has some evidence for UTI prevention in adult women, but there is insufficient evidence for its use in children. Moreover, it is not an appropriate treatment for an active infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgical correction\u003C/strong\u003E of vesicoureteric reflux is not the first-line management in this acute situation. Surgical intervention is typically considered after conservative measures have failed, and is often delayed until the child is older as vesicoureteric reflux can resolve spontaneously in young children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate given the child\u0027s symptoms and signs of active infection. Delaying treatment could lead to worsening of the infection and potential further renal damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaily antibiotic prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for long-term management of vesicoureteric reflux to prevent recurrent UTIs, but it is not the immediate priority in this acute presentation. Prophylaxis would be initiated after the current infection has been treated and the child is well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of vesicoureteric reflux in children involves a multidisciplinary approach. While surgical correction may eventually be necessary for some children, initial management often involves conservative measures such as antibiotic prophylaxis and close monitoring. The decision for surgical intervention is based on factors including the grade of reflux, frequency of infections, and presence of renal scarring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A recurrent urinary tract infection in a child with systemic symptoms and signs should be treated with empirical intravenous antibiotics.","Vesicoureteric reflux in young children is often managed conservatively as it may resolve spontaneously.","DMSA scans are used to detect renal scarring in children with recurrent urinary tract infections."],"references":["Tullus K, Shaikh N. Urinary tract infections in children. Lancet 2020; 395:1659-68."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33920"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11559"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33920"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:23:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T11:47:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4188"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48920"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/152"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cystitis","synonyms":["Urinary tract infection","UTI","Lower UTI","Urinary infection","Urinary tra